The paper discusses deep convolutional neural networks trained on natural images, which suggests that it is likely to belong to the computer vision (cs.CV) sub-category. The paper also discusses the generality versus specificity of neurons in each layer of the network, which suggests that it may also belong to the machine learning (cs.LG) sub-category. Additionally, the paper discusses optimization difficulties related to splitting networks between co-adapted neurons, which suggests that it may also belong to the neural and evolutionary computing (cs.NE) sub-category. The paper also discusses the transferability of features between different datasets and tasks, which suggests that it may also belong to the artificial intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category. Finally, the paper discusses the use of deep neural networks for natural language processing tasks, which suggests that it may also belong to the computational linguistics (cs.CL) sub-category.
